Z, in IE conditional comments aren't subjective to the user agent so I'm guessing that's why Xdega would like them in place of using JavaScript to determine compatibility.<br /><br />If anything I like what Opera already has, the <span style="font-style: italic">window.opera</span> object. I think a reasonable feature would to have non-user agent dependent DOM object properties with the engine name (e.g. Gecko, KHTML, Presto, Trident, WebKit) and then the version however I have to criticize WebKit's build numbers so I would prefer the Safari browser version number and even that is subjective since Chrome shares the WebKit engine. Right here and right now the JavaScript object detection is the only truly reliable means to determine the browser engine and version reliably even if someone is spoofing their user agent.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=47">JAB Creations</a> — Mon May 09, 2011 5:14 pm</p><hr />
